      <h3>üíä Compounded GLP-1s ($179-349/month)</h3>
      <p><strong>Pros:</strong> 50-70% cheaper, same active ingredients, legal from licensed pharmacies</p>
      <p><strong>Cons:</strong> Not FDA-approved, no quality guarantee, insurance typically won't cover</p>
    </div>
    
    <div class="highlight-box" style="background: #dbeafe; border-left-color: #3b82f6;">
      <h3 style="color: #1e40af;">üíé Brand-Name GLP-1s ($1,000-1,400/month)</h3>
      <p style="color: #1e3a8a;"><strong>Pros:</strong> FDA-approved, quality guaranteed, insurance may cover (reducing cost to $25-50/mo)</p>
      <p style="color: #1e3a8a;"><strong>Cons:</strong> Very expensive without insurance, limited telehealth availability</p>
    </div>
    
    <h2>How to Save Money on GLP-1 Medications</h2>
    
    <h3>1. Choose Compounded Over Brand-Name</h3>
    <p>The single biggest cost savings comes from choosing compounded medications. Providers like ${cheapest.slice(0, 3).map(p => p.name).join(', ')} offer compounded semaglutide or tirzepatide for $179-349 per month instead of $1,000+ for Wegovy or Zepbound.</p>
    
    <h3>2. Check Your Insurance Coverage</h3>
    <p>If your insurance covers Wegovy or Zepbound, your copay could be as low as $25-50 per month. Providers like ${providers.filter(p => p.insurance).slice(0, 2).map(p => p.name).join(' and ')} can help navigate insurance coverage. Check eligibility before assuming you need to pay cash.</p>
    
